{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b7d6ce8a-09c2-4e16-a636-528215adcc14","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a .NET tool.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g. `my-mcp-server`).\n- **`OutputType`** must be `Exe` (required for tools).\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get an API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server            # runs via stdio\n```\n\nWould you like me to update your actual `.csproj` file with these properties?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"543ca993-0ebc-41a0-8e2b-4b3eceb047e0","outputTokens":442,"requestId":"3856:2A9B4:6FCC72A:782EF0A:6A03D02D"},"id":"3d93c257-f68e-4576-aa94-e4d7110b350a","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:13:25.242Z","parentId":"300c6afb-6d3e-42c0-8934-d3419fa84a79"}
